  "response": "I apologize, but there's a slight misunderstanding in your question. Metro trains do not necessarily have an even number of bogies (or carriages). The number of bogies can vary depending on several factors:\n\n1. City and transit system requirements\n2. Passenger volume\n3. Train length and platform capacity\n4. Specific design of the metro system\n\nIn many metro systems, the number of bogies can be:\n- Odd or even\n- Typically ranging from 3 to 8 bogies per train\n- Determined by local transportation authorities\n\nSome examples:\n- Delhi Metro: Trains with 6 or 8 bogies\n- New York Subway: Typically 8-10 cars\n- Tokyo Metro: Varies from 8 to 10 cars\n\nThe number of bogies is primarily based on:\n- Passenger demand\n- Infrastructure constraints\n- Economic efficiency\n- Technical specifications\n\nThere's no universal rule mandating an even number of bogies in metro trains.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of metro train design?",
